Principal Component Analysis

Dataset x

This dataset contains 83 individuals and 30 variables.

1. Study of the outliers

The analysis of the graphs does not detect any outlier.

2. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of analyse express 54.3% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 54.3% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is strongly greater than the reference value that equals 15.84%, the variability explained by this plane is thus highly significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 7218 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 2 - Decomposition of the total inertia

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 4 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (68.1% against 28.82%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

3. Description of the plane 1:2

## Warning: ggrepel: 10 unlabeled data points (too many overlaps). Consider increasing max.overlaps

Figure 3.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

Figure 3.2 - Variables factor map (PCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 9, 16, 13, 20, 12, 10, 17, 15, 18 and 21 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis (to the left of the graph).

The group in which the individuals 9, 16, 13, 20, 12, 10, 17, 15, 18 and 21 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for variables like Si, Al, P, K, S, Cu, Fe, Ti, V and Zn (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variables Sb, Mg, Ba, Bi, Pb, As, Pd and Rb (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The group 2 (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Mg, Sb, Ba, Bi, Pb, Pd, As and Ca (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for variables like Si, Al, P, Nb, S, K, Cu, Fe, Ti and Zr (variables are sorted from the weakest).

Note that the variables Si and Sb are highly correlated with this dimension (respective correlation of 0.91, 0.9). These variables could therefore summarize themselve the dimension 1.

The dimension 2 opposes individuals such as 37 (to the top of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis (to the bottom of the graph).

The group in which the individual 37 stands (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Mo, Rb, As, Nb, Zr, Pb and Sr (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable Cr.

The group 2 (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Mg, Sb, Ba, Bi, Pb, Pd, As and Ca (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for variables like Si, Al, P, Nb, S, K, Cu, Fe, Ti and Zr (variables are sorted from the weakest).

5. Classification

Figure 5 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals such as 67. This group is characterized by :

  • low values for variables like Si, Al, P, Nb, Cu, Fe, K, Ti, Zr and S (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 37. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables Mo, Rb, Nb, As, Zr, Pb and Sr (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 2, 3, 4, 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13 and 15. This group is characterized by :
